  "response": "# Investigating Thread Starvation by Background Workers\n\nThread starvation occurs when certain threads monopolize CPU resources, preventing other threads from executing in a timely manner. When a background worker is introduced, it could potentially starve request-handling threads if not properly configured.\n\n## Evidence to Gather\n\n### 1. Thread Utilization Metrics\n- **CPU time distribution**: Measure CPU time allocated to background worker threads vs. request threads\n- **Thread state analysis**: Count of threads in RUNNABLE vs. WAITING/BLOCKED states\n- **Context switch frequency**: Decreased context switches may indicate thread monopolization\n\n### 2. Request Latency Measurements\n- **Before/after comparison**: Compare request latency before and after background worker introduction\n- **Percentile analysis**: Look for increases in p95/p99 latencies which often reveal starvation issues\n- **Correlation analysis**: Plot request latency against background worker activity\n\n### 3. Thread Dump Analysis\n- Capture thread dumps during high-load periods\n- Examine stack traces to identify if request threads are waiting for resources\n- Look for lock contention patterns between worker and request threads\n\n### 4. System-Level Evidence\n- **Load average**: Sudden increases after worker introduction\n- **Run queue length**: More processes waiting for CPU time\n- **I/O wait times**: If the background worker is I/O intensive\n\n### 5. Controlled Experiments\n- **Gradual worker introduction**: Incrementally increase worker thread count/priority\n- **Stress testing**: Simulate high load with and without the worker active\n- **Priority adjustments**: Test different thread priority configurations\n\n## Implementation Approach\n\nTo gather this evidence, you could:\n\n1. Use profiling tools like JVisualVM, async-profiler, or YourKit\n2. Implement metrics collection in your application using Prometheus/Micrometer\n3. Configure thread pool monitoring in your application server\n4. Use OS-level tools like `top`, `vmstat`, or `mpstat` with thread view\n5. Implement canary deployments with the new worker to compare performance\n\nIf starvation is confirmed, solutions might include:\n- Adjusting thread priorities\n- Implementing rate limiting for the background worker\n- Using separate thread pools with appropriate sizing\n- Scheduling background work during low-traffic periods\n- Implementing cooperative multitasking approaches",
